<table  border=0 cellpadding=2 cellspacing=0 awidth=100%>
	   <a name=102086886738060></a>
	   <form action=http://www1.allakhazam.com/perl/strategy/mrate.pl name=f102086886738060><tr><td id=headerrow><a id=sj href=classes.html?class=5&mid=102086886738060>RE: Race?</a> <a id=fs8 href=classes.html?class=5&mid=102086886738060#post><img src=http://everquest.allakhazam.com/static/reply.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=16 width=16></a></td><td align=right id=headerrow valign=bottom><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href=poster.html?user=159038><span id= >Phaelyn</span></a>, <span id= > </span><br><span id=notbold>5 posts</td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 id=headerrow>Posted @ Wed, May 8th 10:41 AM 2002</td>
	   <td id=headerrow align=right><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Good<span id=notbold>[3.50]</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=2>Depends on what you want out of the game.&nbsp;&nbsp;Crunching numbers Ogres make the best melee hands down.  Second Trolls.  Only two other races are worse then Dark Elves as far as melee classes go; Erudites and High Elves.  However, there are other things to consider besides melee stats.  First, regardless of what race you choose, you'll never have the hps/ac of a warrior.  Ac is capped at 100 less then a warrior, not sure about hp.  Second, look at intelligence.  Weaker classes trade melee for intelligence, and if you are a sk and not casting you are foolish.  However, that's still not much of a balancing issue, cause sk's are 3/4 melee and only 1/4 caster.  Lastly, and perhaps the most overlooked difference is dark elven ultravision.  I play a dark elf and nothing compares with my ability to see in dark areas, which I happen to frequent.  Infravision isn't bad, but it doesn't have anything on Ultravision.  This alone is worth considering, fore many, many times I've pulled in place of a more capable tank.  (Yes, I play a DESK)  Another thing to consider is taking advantage of size.  If you are fighting in cramped quarters you can get a lot more dark elves in one area then you can one ogre or troll. (Shamans can help, but we're not talking about how other classes can improve us atm.)  In fact, inattentive ogres/trolls can sometimes lock someone in a corner, such as a cleric w/aggro.<br><br>NONE OF THESE THINGS MATTER ENOUGH TO MAKE OR BREAK A SK DUE SOLEY TO RACE.  Small races WILL have a more difficult time dealing and taking the damage a larger race will, but in my experience that difference doesn't come out to be that much.  If an ogre has 300 more hps then me, that usually only a second more of damage he can take from the mobs I'm usually fighting.  In essence, choose what race appeals to you the most, then take note of that races weaknesses and strive to compensate.<br><br>The MOST important thing a person needs to figure out when choosing to play an sk is his class abilities.  There's no exception to this.  You can twink your sk to hell and back, have super stats and super resist and godlike hps and ac.  If you don't ever learn how to properly use your skills you'll never be an asset to yourself or others, cause melee alone won't make you a worthy sk, regardless of race.<br><br>Nuff about race.  Pick the one that appeals to you and go have fun, and learn what it truely means to be an sk. GL<br>&nbsp;<br> </td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 >&nbsp;</td><td align=right valign=bottom>
	   <span style='font-weight: normal; font-size: 9px;'>[<a href=#top>Top</a>]</span></tr>
